l combustion and flue gas desulfurization (FGD). In power plants, calcite is utilized in the production of calcium carbonate for sulfur dioxide removal from exhaust gases, helping power plants meet environmental regulations. The fine powder form of calcite serves as a critical agent in reducing air pollution by converting harmful sulfur dioxide into a less harmful substance, preventing acid rain and improving air quality. Additionally, calcite's ability to act as a sorbent in the capture and neutralization of pollutants has further fueled its demand in the power industry.<p>As global efforts intensify to transition towards cleaner energy production, the use of calcite in environmental applications has gained considerable traction. The increasing adoption of carbon capture technologies and stricter regulatory standards for power plants is likely to drive the demand for calcite powder. With power plants continuously seeking efficient methods for reducing emissions, calcite's role in enabling sustainable operations and meeting environmental compliance targets is expected to expand, making it an essential material in the sector.<h2>Glass Industry</h2><p>Calcite powder is an essential raw material in the glass manufacturing industry, where it is used as a fluxing agent to lower the melting point of raw materials and improve the overall quality of the glass produced. It acts as an additive to glass batch formulations, helping to control the viscosity of the melt, which results in more uniform and durable glass products. The powder’s high brightness and low iron content make it particularly suitable for the production of high-quality glass products, including flat glass, container glass, and fiberglass. In addition, calcite powder aids in the production of clear and transparent glass, which is highly sought after for both decorative and functional applications.<p>The growing demand for glass in various applications, including construction, automotive, and packaging, contin